    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1931-09-05T11:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1931-09-05T11:00:00-05:00" n="793"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d793">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">825.00 Revolutions/23: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Chile</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Culbertson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Acting Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Santiago</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1931-09-05T12:00:00-04:00"
                            >September 5, 1931—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received 1:20 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>106. Sharp fighting in Talcahuano but Government is now in complete control
                    there. Rebels have surrendered in Valparaiso and Government is concentrating its
                    efforts on Coquimbo. Prohibition placed on transmission of news by cable and
                    telegram. Chief communistic leaders in Santiago have been arrested, city quiet
                    but streetcar strike continues. Situation in Iquique threatening but up to the
                    present no disorders in nitrate fields and copper mines. Large supplies of
                    American-owned fuel oil at Chanaral, Antofagasta, and Tocopilla will probably be
                    principal objective of the fleet. The Government promises to make every effort
                    to give protection but admits difficulty.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Culbertson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
